Location: East Peacham Road/Morrison Hill, Barnet, VT
229–277 S America Pond Rd, Island Pond US-VT 44.75763, -71.73158
Observation Details: In https://ebird.org/vt/checklist/S78976882 I described owling in this location.    This morning, I walked down from the parking lot to the marsh to the south shortly before dawn. I put my speaker on a tree branch, and walked 50 feet past it in order to be able to hear alarm calls from owls. I played NSWO, BOOW, BADO, and GHOW, in that order. After the NSWO and BOOW calls, I heard an owl in the pines to the northeast, around 100m away. The owl itself may have been 50 to 300 feet away - I am not good at judging distances. A very light wind, with clear skies, and 20°F weather with no humidity.     The owl was responding in the same fashion as the previous evening - several notes, never more than five. Here, it was more vocal, with less time in between. However, it was not regular - the notes were evenly spaced in their groups, but there were anywhere from 2-5 notes, and there was anywhere from 5 seconds to a minute gap between them. Again, I wondered if it was a tree branch, and again I think it was not, given the wind gusts. An odd noise. I'm still thinking about it.     After 7 minutes, I heard a ksew call from an NSWO a few hundred feet to the west by northwest. It was a quiet ksew, repeated only once. This was not the same bird.

Location: 229–277 S America Pond Rd, Island Pond US-VT 44.75775, -71.73182
Observation Details: Original note: Rapid call heard twice in response to playback.    Later: I walked down from the parking lot to the marsh to the south shortly after dark. I put my speaker on a tree branch, and walked 50 feet past it in order to be able to hear alarm calls from owls. I played NSWO, BOOW, EASO, LEOW, BADO, and GHOW, generally in that order. After the NSWO, BOOW, and EASO calls, I heard a soft toot - like an NSWO, but very quiet, and only one. This was followed by a break of around a minute, and then another single hoot, two hoots, and five toots in quick succession, each separated by around one to two minutes at least, and then ten minutes, after which I played the other owl calls, and finally then  two hoots, and another five. I heard no other owls, but there may have been a porcupine (the smell was atrocious) in the pines to the northwest, around 100m away. The owl itself may have been 50 to 300 feet away - I am not good at judging distances. A very light wind, with clear skies, and 20°F weather with no humidity.     The calls themselves sounded like a very soft NSWO call, but I wouldn't have been surprised if it was a BOOW. On xeno-canto, I could find no records of NSWO calls that fit this mold. I assumed it was a juvenile bird or a male which was responding softly to my calls, but I don't know why it didn't bark or wail, as this species is won't do to. It may have bill snapped, but I can't tell. The five notes in quick succession matches what I think would be the Rapid Call of the NSWO described on Birds of the World, which makes me think this was an NSWO, as opposed to a quiet (and very, very rare) Boreal Owl.     However, in the morning, at around 5:30, I went back, and I heard this bird again, repeatedly. There was more wind then, and I wonder if it could have just been wind. I doubt it - I've not heard a tree that sounds like this, and I carefully waited for breezes in the morning and it didn't match the timing of the gusts. As I was standing (in the same spot) 50-300 feet away, I would have been surprised if the gusts were significantly different.     In short, I think this was an NSWO response to playback from a stationary bird in the same location in one evening.

I played NSWO as part of my sequence and heard a clear NSWO wail from far to the southeast, possibly in the location of the owl I heard at a previous location at 5:30. For more, see note under owl sp.

I put my speaker on the edge of the railing of the bog, and walked back 50 feet from it. I turned off my headlamp. Conditions were calm, with no wind, cloudy, and 20°F temperatures. The ice in the bog had stopped cracking, so it was very, very quiet - the cars on the distant road sounded like the second coming at times. I played BOOW, NSWO, BADO, and GHOW calls over the course of my time there.     I started with BOOW. After playing the male advertising call from Sibley, once (with three calls in it), I waited. After five minutes, I heard two very loud ksew calls from an Aegolius owl across the bog from me, in a vector from the pathway forward with perhaps 25° shift to the left (or, put another way, at 11:00 to the path's noon). The call was short, under a second, and the second call was nearly identical, with around 10 seconds gap between them. It was sadly not repeated while I was recording.     I then - although it may have been before, and I don't know - heard wing beats from what I presume was an owl behind me. I heard this twice more, the second two certainly after the call. I was unable to visually locate the bird with my headlamp.     I noted the call as being two things: 1) extremely loud, and 2) low. I wonder about the second one, now, and it's possible I was wrong. Certainly, it did not sound squeaky, as many BOOW do on XenoCanto. But it also did not seem mellifluous and gliding, to me, as most of the NSWO sound. I played example calls from eBird on my phone, but due to a mixup with the speaker and eBird's annoying habit of starting playing songs when loading the sounds, the calls were all mixed up and I couldn't easily place them with the one I heard, to the point where I think all I managed was to confuse any owls listening (although this was quiet, meant only for my ears, but surely loud to an owl) and to erase my memory of the call. In the future, I will endeavor not to do this. In any event, the call was not repeated.     I played NSWO around five to ten minutes later, and heard a clear NSWO wail from far to the southeast, possibly in the location of the owl I heard at a previous location at 5:30.    The first bird may or may not have been an NSWO - it may have been a BOOW. However, several things would be odd for BOOW: first, it is exceedingly rare here. Second, the "low" quality I remembered at the time doesn't match with Pieplow's description of skiew calls (https://earbirding.com/blog/archives/824). However, I'm not sure about NSWO, either: for one, it responded to BOOW calls, and I hadn't played NSWO calls yet. Second, it was really loud. I was shocked by it. The NSWO I had heard but 30 minutes earlier was very weak in comparison. Third, it didn't sound as mellifluous, but more cut-off to my ears (whose memory I don't entirely trust).     Who knows.

*Rare. Jumbo-poll 50% larger than ‘flammea’ in proximity. Back one or two shades darker brown than flammea with a chocolatey brown wash in the face. Streaking extensive along sides of breast becoming darker and longer/thicker streaks along the flanks. Tail noticeably long land thick. Throat patch notably long on this individual, extending almost into the upper breast. Very classic example of the taxon- photos tba, maybe in flight shots?

*Rare, at least two photo’d. Darkly marked jumbo-poll with long throat patch. One was a different bird than earlier— dwarfed the core around it and had an interesting charcoal grayish tone to the face above the chocolatey brown throat wash. Second in flight shots- bird from this morning?

I scanned this flock looking for Hoary from the moment I saw the size of the flock. Given more than 40 birds, I wanted to see if it was possible there was a hoary. For the first few minutes there was nothing, but then I noticed a single bird that seemed larger and whiter than the others. I lost it, as the birds kept flying into the birches and back again. During one of these, I found myself blocking the driveway, and someone, who I believe now to be Kevin, said I was alright and that a Hoary had been seen there several weeks prior, but not recently. I said I'd keep looking then, but didn't mention that I'd seen a lighter bird (and I'm not sure why. I think it was just a social gaff, as seems common for me. Also a social gaff - I thought this person was Charles Harcourt, whose checklist I had seen that directed me here, but it was probably Kevin, as Charles was up in Moose Bog at the time, which I can tell now by a checklist he submitted here. My bad. Thanks, Kevin.)    Once I scanned the group again, I found the frostier bird, and wrote this: "Larger bird with frosty appearance, best seen when compared to other redpolls on platform. White undertail coverts without streaking, with minimal streaking on side and a pale breast. Bill slightly smaller, with a pushed in appearance. Alerted five minutes before to known Hoary presence a week or two ago, and seen shortly after."     To add to that now: It did seem larger and whiter, although the whiteness was not " stick-out-like-sore-thumb" purity, and the top and neck seemed dun. It had two to three streaks on the flanks - they were present, but were not anywhere near as thick or many as on the other redpolls, which I sometimes could have confused for Pine Siskins. What impressed me about this bird also was the thickness of the neck; it seemed bullish. I didn't get a very good look at the undertail coverts, but from what I saw they were not streaked, although I've often seen a black spot on the vent that can be confusing - I did not see that on this bird. I never saw the top of the rump, as its wings covered it. I believe this is the same bird seen in this checklist from Kevin, later in the day: https://ebird.org/checklist/S79027839.
Larger, chonky bird with white coverts and rump. Frostier than others. Small bib. At feeder.

While looking at the flock of Redpolls feasting on some grasses, I noticed one bird that was grayer and, to quote the general parlance used, "frostier" than the others. I took some photos, as my friend had my binoculars at the time, so I was using my Nikon 500mm as a stand-in binocular. I noticed minimal streaking on the side, but my views were not ideal, and I never quite saw the head or breast clearly. However, I did note that this bird had a white rump, and clean undertail coverts. The birds flew after a couple of minutes, and I wasn't able to find the flock or this particular bird again.     Assuredly a continuing bird, one of several identified by others at this location. However, the flock I had was roughly 150 birds, not 450, so I suspect I didn't see the whole flock or some has moved on.

Continuing bird in this flock visiting these feeders. Frustratingly unable to get a photo. The first field mark that caught my eye on this bird was the noticeably reduced side streaking in comparison to nearby Common Redpolls. Overall lighter bird with short, pushed-in bill, frosted rump and scapulars, pure white undertail coverts, did not notice any streaking when seen perched briefly. Not big or pale enough to be the nominate subspecies.

Originally thought there was one, but upon reviewing photos realized there were two individuals present. Both showed limited side streaking, shorter bill, white rump. Bird #2 with a more forward-oriented 'poll' and cleaner undertail. Bird #1 had a single undertail streak, but the rest of the field marks noted seem to fit well with female/immature Hoary Redpoll. Interestingly, the Hoary we observed on the feeder would frequently remain in place, even when the rest of the Common Redpoll flock took off on several occasions.

*Rare. All carefully ID-ed in scopes- back color/ rump streaking, undertail, side streaking, etc. least three photo documented and up to five in the flock with a couple browner immatures left at core/hore and one probable ad male seen briefly. Awesome show! Count subject to change based on photo review. Expected ssp.

*Rare and high. Came back this afternoon to get better documentation of birds I saw this morning and managed to photograph/ study quite a few of these. Two very light classic examples, two with slightly darker streaking/ larger bills, and an adult male. All birds assessed for rump coloration, undertail streaking, side streaking, and bill size. At least three photo’d here, adult male notes below, and a resighting of this bird from the morning :https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/299246351.    Adult male notes: Seen in the scope foraging on ground then into ragweed for a good 30sec before flock flushed. Light-tan faced poll with tiny bill, disconnected streaks that faded to nothing by midbreast, diffuse pink wash on upper breast, clean undertail- no streaks that I could see, boxy head while foraging, back seen next to flammea and noticeably lighter though more beige than gray, clean white rump in flight.

Certainly 2, likely more in this still-pretty-large flock. Two apparent adult females seen, with limited side streaking, all-white undertail coverts, frosty backs, scapulars, and white rumps, and short, pushed-in bills. At least one photographed, maybe both.

Found when reviewing photos, blended in much better than the hornemanni, but still shows shorter bill, limited side streaking, and overall frostier appearance than nearby flammeas.

Thrilling bird, first photo documentation of this subspecies in Vermont!    Spotted first by Richard L., who shouted "Hoary!" Ridiculously easy to pick out this bird among the flock of flammeas due to its size and paleness. Largest and frostiest redpoll I've ever seen. Identified as the nominate subspecies by lack of any noticeable side-streaking, massive size, and thick white wing bars. Possibly a male, as there appears to be a bit of a pink wash on the breast. Differentiated from leucistic or "Angel" Common Redpoll by presence of some dark coloration on wings, forward-facing 'poll' and overall more Hoary-ish structure, including body size and bill length. Confirmed as A. h. hornemanni by Matt Young.
